%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\begin{abstract}
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% ~150-200 words summarizing the key contributions
% Hook: existing tools give false confidence
% Solution: calibrated Bayesian verdicts
% Results: highlight key evaluation findings

Timing side-channel attacks remain a real threat to cryptographic implementations.
Existing detection tools like \dudect and \tlsfuzzer provide binary pass/fail verdicts
but don't indicate when measurement noise makes the result unreliable. Developers
see ``pass'' and assume their code is safe, unaware the test lacked sufficient
statistical power to detect exploitable leaks.
%
We present \tacet, a timing side-channel detection library that reports
\emph{Inconclusive} when evidence is insufficient rather than forcing a verdict.
This three-way decision framework (Pass/Fail/Inconclusive) prevents false confidence.
%
\tacet uses Bayesian inference over the Wasserstein-1 (earth-mover) distance, outputting
posterior probabilities $\prob{\text{leak} > \theta \given \text{data}}$ instead of p-values.
This single metric captures both uniform timing shifts and rare tail effects, providing
superior detection power for cache-timing attacks and other microarchitectural leaks
that manifest as outliers in a small fraction of measurements.
The system handles autocorrelated measurements via block bootstrap, detects degraded
conditions through quality gates, and tracks an explicit measurement floor.
%
We evaluate \tacet on synthetic benchmarks and real cryptographic libraries.
Where other tools produce unreliable results under noise and autocorrelation,
\tacet maintains calibrated verdicts by returning Inconclusive when appropriate.
The library is implemented in Rust with C/C++, Go, and JavaScript bindings.

\end{abstract}

%===============================================================================
% SECTION 1: INTRODUCTION (~1.25 pages)
%===============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Timing side-channel detection is part of validating cryptographic implementations.
Existing tools provide binary pass/fail verdicts without indicating when measurement
conditions make the result unreliable. When noise or autocorrelation degrades data
quality, these tools may output ``pass'' even when the evidence is insufficient.
A developer sees a passing result and assumes their code has no exploitable leak,
unaware the test couldn't actually detect anything.

Timing side-channels remain a real threat. Lucky~Thirteen~\cite{lucky13} exploited
CBC padding timing in TLS with just a few thousand queries. The Raccoon Attack~\cite{raccoon}
recovered DH secrets from timing differences on the order of microseconds. The MARVIN
attack~\cite{marvin} showed that RSA PKCS\#1 v1.5 implementations in over 40 libraries
leak plaintext through nanosecond-scale timing differences in big-integer arithmetic. These attacks work across different settings: network-accessible APIs (where
Timeless Timing Attacks~\cite{timeless} achieve LAN-like precision via HTTP/2 request
multiplexing), and co-located adversaries in SGX enclaves or containers.

The standard approach compares execution time distributions between fixed and
random inputs. \dudect~\cite{dudect}, the most widely used tool, applies Welch's
t-test and reports a binary verdict. More recent tools like \rtlf~\cite{rtlf} and
\silent~\cite{silent} use quantile comparisons with bootstrap-based inference.
But all existing tools share the same limitation: they output binary verdicts
without distinguishing between ``no leak above threshold'' and ``we couldn't tell.''

This limitation is well-documented by practitioners. Trail of Bits notes that
dudect's ``time measurements are as reliable as the conditions allow''—noise from
concurrent processes can mask leakage signals, results may not reproduce across
machines, and critically, ``even if Dudect finds no leakages, it doesn't guarantee
that the code is free from timing vulnerabilities''~\cite{trailofbits-dudect}.
Under noisy conditions (common in CI with shared resources and variable load),
binary tools may output ``pass'' when the evidence is genuinely insufficient.
False positives waste developer time; false negatives give unwarranted confidence
in vulnerable code.

We present \tacet, a timing side-channel detection tool with three possible
verdicts: \textsc{Pass} (high confidence of no leak), \textsc{Fail} (high
confidence of leak), or \textsc{Inconclusive} (insufficient evidence). \tacet
computes the posterior probability $\prob{\text{leak} > \theta \given \text{data}}$
through Bayesian inference and only emits Pass or Fail when this probability
crosses a decision threshold (5\% or 95\%). When evidence is insufficient,
quality gates detect this and return Inconclusive rather than guessing.

\silent~\cite{silent} introduced an important insight: timing distributions should
be compared via quantiles rather than means, capturing both uniform shifts (from branches)
and tail effects (from cache behavior). However, their 9-quantile approach has a fundamental
limitation for rare tail effects: when only a small fraction of samples exhibit the leak,
the signal dilutes across 9 dimensions, making detection unreliable. We build on \silent's
insight but use the Wasserstein-1 (W₁) distance—a single metric that captures the same
distributional information with superior power for rare tail effects. Transporting outlier
probability mass across the distribution makes rare leaks visible in a single metric
without multiple-comparison corrections.

Our contributions beyond the W₁ statistic include: a robust Bayesian framework with
calibrated three-way verdicts (Pass/Fail/Inconclusive), quality gates that detect
degraded measurement conditions, and an explicit measurement floor that prevents
claiming ``no leak'' when the system can't resolve effects at the requested threshold.

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Contributions}
\label{sec:contributions}

% Bulleted list of contributions (usually 3-5)
% Each contribution should be concrete and verifiable

Our contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Calibrated verdicts}: We introduce a three-way decision framework
          (Pass/Fail/Inconclusive) that explicitly reports when evidence is
          insufficient, rather than forcing potentially incorrect verdicts.

    \item \textbf{Interpretable uncertainty}: \tacet outputs posterior probabilities
          $\prob{\text{leak} > \theta \given \text{data}}$ rather than p-values,
          providing directly interpretable uncertainty quantification.

    \item \textbf{Robustness to dependent data}: We employ block bootstrap on the
          acquisition stream to handle autocorrelation in timing measurements,
          a common violation of iid assumptions that invalidates standard
          statistical tests.

    \item \textbf{Practical tooling}: We provide a production-ready implementation
          in Rust with C/C++, Go, and JavaScript (via WASM) bindings, designed for CI integration.

    \item \textbf{Comprehensive evaluation}: We evaluate \tacet against existing
          tools (\dudect, \tlsfuzzer, \rtlf, \silent) on synthetic benchmarks
          with controlled effect sizes, autocorrelation, and noise levels,
          as well as real cryptographic libraries.
\end{enumerate}

%===============================================================================
% SECTION 2: BACKGROUND & RELATED WORK (~1.25 pages)
%===============================================================================
\section{Background and Related Work}
\label{sec:background}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Timing Side-Channel Attacks}
\label{sec:background:attacks}

Timing side-channels exist when a cryptographic implementation's execution time
depends on secret data. An attacker who can measure this timing (either directly
or through statistical analysis of many queries) may recover secret keys or
plaintext. The threat model varies by attacker capability:

\paragraph{Remote network attackers.}
Traditional timing attacks over the internet face millisecond-level jitter.
Van~Goethem~\etal~\cite{timeless} showed that HTTP/2 request multiplexing
enables timeless timing attacks: relative timing between concurrent requests
eliminates network jitter, giving remote attackers LAN-like precision ($\sim$100\,ns).

\paragraph{Adjacent network attackers.}
Attackers on the same LAN or in the same data center can achieve microsecond
precision. The Raccoon Attack~\cite{raccoon} exploited 1--10\,$\mu$s timing
differences in TLS-DH implementations to recover pre-master secrets.

\paragraph{Co-located attackers.}
In shared environments (cloud VMs, containers, SGX enclaves), attackers may
achieve cycle-level timing resolution through cache timing, hyperthreading
interference, or direct hardware access. KyberSlash~\cite{kyberslash} demonstrated
that $\sim$20-cycle timing leaks in post-quantum implementations can be exploited
by co-located adversaries.

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Existing Detection Tools}
\label{sec:background:tools}

Several tools exist for detecting timing side-channels during development.

\paragraph{\dudect~\cite{dudect}.}
The most widely used tool. \dudect applies Welch's t-test to compare timing
distributions between fixed and random inputs. It's simple, fast, and available
in C with Rust bindings. But it compares only means (missing tail effects),
assumes normality (violated by timing data), outputs only a t-statistic (not
a probability), and gives no indication when measurement noise makes the result
unreliable.

\paragraph{\tlsfuzzer~\cite{tlsfuzzer}.}
A network-level timing analysis tool that applies multiple statistical tests
(Wilcoxon, Friedman, etc.) to TLS implementations. It mitigates autocorrelation
via paired sampling and provides bounded Type-I error, but requires complex setup
for protocol fuzzing and outputs binary verdicts without uncertainty quantification.

\paragraph{\rtlf~\cite{rtlf}.}
Introduced at USENIX Security 2024, \rtlf compares nine deciles between timing
distributions using an i.i.d.\ bootstrap with 10,000 iterations. This captures
distributional differences beyond means. However, the i.i.d.\ bootstrap assumes
independent samples---violated when timing measurements exhibit autocorrelation
from cache state or CPU frequency scaling. \rtlf outputs binary verdicts and
operates only on pre-collected measurement files (no integrated measurement).

\paragraph{\silent~\cite{silent}.}
The most statistically sophisticated prior work. \silent uses a 9-quantile test
statistic with $m$-dependent block bootstrap that handles autocorrelated data.
It provides bounded Type-I error via relevance testing against a user-defined
threshold $\Delta$. However, the 9-dimensional test statistic has limited power
for rare tail effects---when only a small fraction of samples exhibit the leak
(e.g., cache-timing attacks), the signal dilutes across 9 quantiles, making reliable
detection difficult even with large sample sizes. Additionally, \silent outputs
only binary verdicts:
when evidence is marginal, it must choose Pass or Fail rather than reporting
uncertainty. The paper acknowledges stationarity as a limitation but doesn't
actively detect violations.

